                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="padding-left-40 padding-right-40">
                    {# INTRO #}
                    <div class="c-learn-article-page__introduction">
                        A unique value proposition is a short, clear and compelling message that states WHAT’S NEW in
                        your innovation, and WHY it is worth consumers’ money. It’s what a consumer would say to
                        another, to advise them to try it.
                    </div>
                    {# WHY #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">Why?</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        <span class="bold">There are already so many products and services out there.</span> Why would
                        people buy yours instead of something else? Why would they recommend it to someone?
                        <br><br>
                        An idea is not unique per say. It’s consumers, and what they will like about it, that make it
                        unique. The sooner you try to understand what makes that uniqueness, the easier it will be to
                        communicate and to scale. It will also prevent you from late learnings with costly iterations.
                    </p>
                    <img src="{{ asset('/images/learn/nailing/nailing-vp-why.png') }}" alt=""
                         class="c-learn-article-page__image">
                    {# WHAT #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">What?</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        <span class="bold">Think of a tweet or a punchline. Short and impactful are key to make it easy to communicate and to remember.</span>
                        <br><br>
                        It’s tempting to say everything about your innovation, but the more you say the less specific
                        you are. By being generic, your consumers will not be able to identify your innovation as a
                        solution for their specific need.
                    </p>
                    <img src="{{ asset('/images/learn/nailing/nailing-vp-what.jpg') }}" alt=""
                         class="c-learn-article-page__image">
                    <div class="c-learn-article-page__quote">
                        <div class="title">
                            <span class="quote-left"></span>
                            <span>
                                Your customers are the judge, jury, and<br/>
                                executioner of your value proposition. They<br/>
                                will be merciless if you don’t find fit!
                            </span>
                            <span class="quote-right"></span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="subtitle">Scott Belsky</div>
                    </div>
                    {# HOW #}
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">How?</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        <span class="bold">Don’t be upset if it doesn’t come right away.</span> Nailing a good value
                        proposition is a challenge for every innovator. Don’t be afraid to ask for feedback (if you are
                        a project manager, use the feedback tool on your project page), to tweak words, to iterate… to
                        come up with the best version you can think of so far. Do it as much as possible before you
                        scale. It will cost you less and avoid delays.
                        <br><br>
                        Think about a simple way to tell your story: a functional or emotional benefit, a tone of voice,
                        visual symbols, a color code and a name… since you must choose, which do you think will resonate
                        most with consumers?
                        <br><br>
                        <span class="font-work-sans-600 font-size-24 line-height-30">To define it, keep in mind these 3 core principles:</span>
                        <br><br>

                        <span class="font-work-sans-600 font-size-22 line-height-30">1. Value is always contextual</span><br/>
                        It should appeal only to certain people, for specific occasions, in a certain type of
                        environment – at home, in a high energy club, in a low energy bar… Do not try to talk to
                        everybody, concentrate on solving only one problem at a time. Trying to answer to several
                        operational objectives puts your value at risk. <br/><br/>

                        <span class="font-work-sans-600 font-size-22 line-height-30">2. Value is polarizing</span><br/>
                        It has got traction naturally. Its singularity is perceived by early adopters, the ones who will
                        buy you first. Do not try to talk to everybody otherwise nobody will notice you.<br/><br/>

                        <span class="font-work-sans-600 font-size-22 line-height-30">3. Value provokes word of mouth</span><br/>
                        It should be easily understood by a friend, so no marketing jargon shall be used. There should
                        be no need for huge marketing push campaigns either. It is all about aspirational stories
                        capturing people’s attention, that can become viral.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="c-learn-article-page__emphasize-section">
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading subject">Examples</h2>
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">Jameson Caskmates</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        A genuine and authentic story about two craftsmen collaborating to
                        make something greater than the sum of it's parts. Finished in Craft
                        Stout Barrels for new notes of chocolate, coffee &amp; butterscotch, it is
                        the perfect whiskey for Craft Beer Drinkers.
                    </p>
                    <img src="{{ asset('/images/learn/nailing/nailing-vp-caskmates-example.jpg') }}" alt=""
                         class="c-learn-article-page__image">
                    <br/>
                    <h2 class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph-heading">Crown Royal Apple</h2>
                    <p class="c-learn-article-page__paragraph">
                        Launched in 2016 in the US, Crown Royal Apple sold 1.6M cases its first year. In its
                        TV commercial, the value proposition is expressed in a very simple and
                        straightforward way: at the end of the ad you know what you can expect / what
                        you get, and how to enjoy it.
                    </p>
                    <a href="https://www.ispot.tv/ad/Aoct/crown-royal-regal-apple-smooth" target="_blank"
